d 'SRH_TEST': module for computing the Scheirer-Ray-Hare nonparametric two-way analysis of variance test  
d
d  srh_test performs the Scheirer-Ray-Hare (SRH) test, a
d nonparametric alternative to two-way factorial ANOVA. The test
d was introduced by Scheirer, Ray, and Hare (1976) as an extension 
d of the Kruskal-Wallis one-way test to designs with two crossed
d factors and their interaction. The command displays the standard
d ANOVA table augmented with two additional columns, H, the
d Scheirer-Ray-Hare test statistic for each term, and Prob>chi2,
d the p-value for H based on the chi-squared distribution with
d degrees of freedom equal to those of the term. Like the
d Kruskal-Wallis test, the SRH test does not require normality. It
d assumes that observations are independent and that the response
d variable is at least ordinal. The chi-squared approximation
d improves with larger sample sizes; results should be interpreted
d cautiously in small samples. The SRH test is intended for
d balanced factorial designs, where every combination of
d factor_var1 and factor_var2 levels contains the same number of
d observations. With unbalanced designs the test may produce
d unreliable results, because the sums of squares and MS(total) are
d distorted when cell sizes differ. If the design is unbalanced,
d alternative approaches should be considered. The SRH test has
d lower statistical power than parametric two-way ANOVA and is
d considered conservative relative to the parametric alternative
d (Dytham 2003). When the normality assumption of parametric ANOVA
d is plausible, that test is preferred. Post-hoc pairwise
d comparisons should be performed separately if significant effects
d are found. 
d
d KW: Scheirer-Ray-Hare test
d KW: two-way analysis of variance
d KW: ANOVA
d
d Requires: Stata version 11
d
d Distribution-Date: 20260407
d
d Author: Ariel Linden, Linden Consulting Group, LLC
d Support: email alinden@@lindenconsulting.org
d
f srh_test.ado
f srh_test.sthlp
